#### **3.**	Basic tables , SQL queries and databases

This model is used for the optimization process of a small data set by using as origin the city of Wageningen with **_9_** zip codes  areas (consisted of 4 digits) and **_33_** destination  recreation areas in the surrounding of Wageningen. For Wageningen 9 four-digits zip codes were selected : from 6701 to 6709 (see also **zip_code_coordinates table**, (see also **Appendix A**). For this model four digits zip codes were selected in place of the six-codes (alphanumeric) because the distances of the four digits zip codes are small in the small city of Wageningen when comparing with the big cities as for example Utrecht, Amsterdam or Rotterdam. Furthermore it is easier to check up the model with less amount of data when we used 4 digits zip codes. The 33 recreation areas were selected having as maximum distance from the zip codes in Wageningen about 37 km. (see **Table_9_zip_code_RecrID_distances** (see also **Appendix A**). The distances were estimated by using the Google maps with  three different transport types: on foot, bicycle and car. The zip codes maps and the recreation areas can be viewed by in pdf file format created by the main script of the model on the files: **zip code locations in Wageningen.pdf** and **Recreation areas around Wageningen.pdf**.

Each zip code area was consisted of **_52_** household types, group types combinations (**_10_** household types with **_18_**  group types combinations). The group types represents the recreationists who come from a certain household types. These **_52_** combinations, with or without children, age of the adults and age of the  children recreationists including or not a dog etc.are represented on table: **Table14_hgpID_groups_types** (see **Appendix A**)

Every recreationist has a certain maximum budget per year and a maximum daily budget for recreation (see also **Table_16_hgpID_min_max_budgets**  (see **Appendix A**).

On the table **Table10_hgpID_activity_budget**  (see **Appendix A**) were given the maximum and minimum number of times per activity as well as the minimum and maximum time to spend per activity (in minutes).

On **Table_2_RecrID_type_coordinates_prices**  (see **Appendix A**) we have the type of recreation area and the entrance prices of sights (for adult, child and parking).

On **Table_3_RecrID_activity_pattern**  (see **Appendix A**) were denoted the recreational activities

On the **Table_5_activities_definiton-costs**  (see **Appendix A**) were represented the fixed costs per activity, the costs per hour per activity, the cost per person per activity and finally the costs per hour and per person per activity.

**Table_7_zip_hgpID_budget** (see **Appendix A**) were the combinations of the zip codes and the 52 combinations of household types group types.

The table **Time_segment_selected**  (see **Appendix A**) is the combinations of the recreation areas and the time segments (**4** in this example) number of visits per time segment and the available time per time segment.

All the abovementioned tables are on the database: **Wageningen_Basic_Tables_2018.sqlite** for the Mac operation system and also for the Windows operation system. These basic tables were required for the setting up the queries in order to obtain the **Final_table**. These queries were run in a special R function: **Run_Queries.R**

These **_11_** basic tables are required for setting up the queries and the tables: **zip_code_coordinates** together with the table **Table_2_RecrID_type_coordinates_prices** are required for the map presentation on the files: **zip_code_Wageningen_map.pdf** and **Recreation_areas.pdf** for mapping the zip codes and recreation areas surrounding the Wageningen city.

It is possible also for the user to use the abovementioned queries of the function **Run_Queries.R** in his own database in order to produce the **Final_table**. 

The script written on the file:**Wageningen_SQLite_E_2018.R** search automatically the required operation system (Mac or Windows) and the presence or absence of the table **Final_table** in the database.

In order the user have a quick view of the observations of the **Basic tables** as well as of the **Final_table** this can be obtained  by clicking the two files with the extension **_Rmd_** (Markdown files):
