###### **4.4** Construction of the Hessian matrix

**1.**	The number of locations had been spread out as much as possible per groupsRecr_at (these were the groups with the same activities on the same time segments per destination area), activity_pattern and groupsRecr_act_ts (these were the groups with the same time segments per groupsRecr_at and activities).

We used the vector loc (size: 48 x 1) which is the number_of_locations column of the data3b matrix (size: 48 x 1) (11).
By using the the reciprocal of the number of locations per groupsRecr_at, activity_pattern and groupsRecr_act_ts (11) we generated the diagonal matrix m1 (48 x 48) **(19)** (see in **Wageningen_Table_Procedures_excel** folder: **Procedures_ACRER**.xlsx, Excel sheet: **quadprog **(3)** ).

**2.**	The number of locations had been spread out as much as possible per groupsRecr_at (these were the groups with the same activities in the same time segments per destination area)

First we had constructed the design1 matrix by using the model.matrix(~fgroupsRecr_at - 1) and by taking the transpose of this 	matrix and by summing per row we got the number of groupsRecr_at per level groupsRecr_at **(20)**. Then by dividing design1 with the number of groupsRecr_at per level groupsRecr_at we got the final design1 matrix **(21)**. By multiplying the final design1 matrix with the number_of_locations column of the data3b matrix we got the number of locations per level groupsRecr_at (Li) **(22)**. 
The matrix **m3** **(23)** of the Hessian matrix was the proportion of the number of locations per groupsRecr_at (see in **Wageningen_Table_Procedures_excel** folder: **Procedures_ACRER**.xlsx. (1)) 

**3.**	Construction of the matrix **m5** (the proportions of maximum number of times per activity pattern)

From the matrix ActMax (size: 10 x 2) **(24)** where the first column is the activity patern levels (10) and the second column is the maximum number of times per activity. The sum of the second column sumi is the maximum number of visits for the 10 activities. First we generated the diagonal matrix dia5 (10 x 10) where this matrix has as diagonal elements the fraction: 
\begin{equation}
\frac
 1{sum_i^2}\, (25)
\end{equation}

From the Table_l1 the sum of the second column sumi = 368 ->

\begin{equation}
\frac
 1{sum_i^2}\, = 0.0000074
\end{equation}


